title: For Sale:  adamSlater82@outlook.com
postcontent: I also take trades like hunting rifles, tactical rifles, handguns and quality optics. Just email me directly at adamslater82@outlook.com Maybe we can work out a trade or use it as a partial down payment.This item is new, Noreen has created the ONLY SEMI-AUTOMATIC .300 WIN MAG and .338 Lapua on the market. The BAD NEWS is a custom-made AR-style rifle that is chambered in the increasingly popular 338 Lapua as well as the powerful 300 WIN MAG. These cartridges give you much greater velocity and power than the typical .308, and as far as ballistics are concerned, the BAD NEWS rifle is going to be the flatter shooting gun for long range shots. The BAD NEWS rifle is a piston-driven semi-auto; this means you can expect greater range and a higher level of reliability by running a cleaner and cooler rifle. The muzzle break on these Noreen’s significantly suppresses recoil. Additionally, the semi-auto nature of the rifle will naturally recoil less than a bolt action because part of the felt recoil is going to chamber the next round. Lighter recoil is a huge advantage when you’re looking for a rifle with a faster and more accurate follow-up shot. This piston-driven system is unlike any other AR-10 on the market. The piston movement is strictly in the action, after the bullet has already left the barrel. This is a huge advantage on a precision rifle compared to conventional piston driven setups found in standard AR's. In those rifles, an LWRC REPR, POF P308, etc. the piston runs parallel to the barrel and moves while the bullet is still in the barrel creating unwanted barrel harmonics which adversely affect accuracy. This rifle's piston is located in the receiver and not along the barrel so the bullet is out of the barrel by the time the piston is working to chamber another round and keep your action cool and clean with no gas ever entering the action. The semi-automatic will not only give you a much faster follow-up shot, it also allows you to stay focused on your target, optic and the trigger, instead of having to manually operate a bolt-action rifle; all subsequent rounds are chambered by the rifle itself during the gas or blowback operation of the action. The weapon easily disassembles like the standard AR for quick and easy cleaning and reassembly. The piston system drastically reduces fouling, and no venting means no holes for dirt and other contaminants to enter the system. The full-length Picatinny rail on the receiver will allow you to mount scopes, lights, lasers, bipods, bayonets, etc. The adjustable cheek rest stock option is an added upgrade free bonus.The innovative Noreen Bad News .338 Lapua provides tactical marksmen with the performance of a powerful and proven long range cartridge with the numerous advantages of the venerable AR platform. The Noreen 338 Lapua weighs only 13 pounds, and it vastly outperforms comparable bolt-action sniper rifles. This rifle comes with a custom muzzle-break and semi-auto action that significantly suppresses recoil. In the AR tradition, the Bad News 338 Lapua disassembles quickly for easy cleaning, then reasembles with no loss of zero. The familiar fit and feel of a conventional AR rifle makes the transition to the more powerful sniper rifle seamless. This Noreen includes an ultra-heavy duty Plano case, which is far superior to a pelican style case. 100% Made in the USA.

title: For Sale:  Colt 1849 Pocket Model, Tiffany Gripped/Engraved
postcontent: Tiffany gripped Model 1849 Colt Pocket Model.  A truly unique revolver, being the only known Tiffany gripped Model 1849 Colt with the American Eagle motif.  According to Robert Jordan and Darrow Watt, authors of "Colt's Pocket '49, It's Evolution".  During the percussion era, four designs were available:  the American eagle, the Mexican Eagle, the Civil War Battle Scene, and the Missionary and Child scene. We only know of two Pocket 49's that were outfitted with Tiffany style grips, both are one line New Yorkers.  One has an American Eagle, the other a Mexican Eagle design".  This gun was advertised by Al Kelley and Jack Malloy in 1967 as having 10% original silver and gold finish, very clean and crisp, with no rust or pitting, and factory engraved by Gustave Young, with original Tiffany grips.  Since then the finish has been restored and it has been cased with excellent accessories.  The condition of the gun and case is exceptional.  The engraving is sharp and totally untouched and the bore is nearly mint.  This gun did not need polishing when it was restored, the original silver and gold having simply drifted with age, being very thin from its 1863 manufacture date.  The cylinder scene is crisp and complete and of course, all numbered parts are matching.  Truely outstanding, this is certainly an investment piece, because of its rarity and condition.
